Simple OpenSCAD module to create straight and curved code 83/100 tracks. You will need the rails, all though this will create the ties and track it self.  
Tracks can be expensive for this hobby, and they are just plastic so I figured to get the rails and attempt to print my own tracks. I finally have something I'm happy with and seems to do the trick.  
I'm using code 83 rails, all though I believe code 100 will work as well. You can adjust the 'size' of the rail with the RAIL_SIZE variable. Defaults to 110, which is what I'm using for the code 83.  
Included is a simple 6" straight piece, and a 24" radius curve in 12 segments. This is what would fit on my 8x8 bed.

Load the track_v2.scad into openscad, the two modules STRAIGHT and CURVE is what you will use to create the tracks. STRAIGHT(length=mm); // Length in mm
CURVE(radius=in,segments=xx); // radius in inches, segments = # of peices to make a full circle

Stihl offered a two piece part for this for many years, but stopped making them.  This is a single piece part that I modeled in 123D that works just fine and prints pretty quickly.

The part just screws in place.  The tolerances are tight so you many need to file the part if the print is less than perfect.  I printed this on a MB2 at "High" detail with in-fill set to 40% to increase the rigidity a bit.

description.text: A simple 35mm negative holder for scanning negatives using a DSLR. The opening on one piece is larger than the other, that side faces the flash. It's to ensure the light hits the whole negative. I put tape to avoid scratching the negative, using a felt type material may work better but it would require modifying the design to make the inside track deeper. So far I haven't had any scratches. Also, not shown in the pictures, you should have some diffusing material between the flash and the negative. I just used two sheets of paper. Here is a blog post I made that details the experiences and results I've had with this setup: http://www.edtse.com/?p=15909 Overall the results have been great. Image quality blows away any flatbed scanner, dust is easier to handle, and I don't have to worry about film curling.

LED: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J9cEAGTLaC8

title: 440 MHz 4 Element Yagi
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is a 4 element Yagi antenna for the 440 MHz frequency. I have added an initial SCAD document to attempt parameterizing the creation of the element spacing. NOTE
There is a limitation on the frequency that the SCAD document. Do not use any frequency above 440 MHz as it will bork the calculations. NOTE
Customizer WILL NOT work with the parametric SCAD file. The only way to customize this part is through OpenSCAD at the time of this note, and should things change so will this note.

There are three pieces to this project. The total count of printed parts are: (1) 440Element_End.stl
(2) 440Element_Segment.stl
(1) 440Element_Mount_Tap.stl Suggested printing with 0.300 mm layer height and 20% infill {Shown in Picture} Once all required pieces are printed, set the notch connector into the end of the next segment and tap together with a hammer. Do Not haul off and really hit the printed parts as they will shatter. A gentle tap until the pieces sit together is more than enough. The order of assembly is shown in AssemblyOrder.png. Essentially: Segment > Mount_Tap > Segment > End I used metal coat hangers for the actual elements and their lengths are {inches | mm}: Reflector Segment {13.27" | 337.058mm}
Driven / Mount_Tap {12.87" | 326.898mm}
Director 1 Segment {11.915" | 302.641mm}
Director 2 / End {11.915" | 302.641mm} The Mount_Tap section is a small bit tricky if you have never messed with a yagi before. The element does not run all the way through the support. What I did here was slightly bend one end of the hanger, then start it through the support hole on the side of the segment. Then once it was in the larger hole, I used a wood screw to push the end further down the hole, and ensure that the end was bare metal. From here one wire {ground or center} of the coax cable is attached to the screw, and then finish tightening the screw. This makes one connection, or tap, to the antenna. Repeat on the other side. Once the center taps are secured, trim the ends of the hangers to length. For all other elements, measure out the appropriate length of wire, then put a small bend in the middle. Push the hanger through the support until it has even amounts of wire showing on either side. The bend will hold the element in place! NOTE
Always check your antenna using an SWR meter before attempting to transmit using any home made antenna, your transmit amplifier will thank you. Edit
I went in and put the proper terms for each segment above. I realized that I was probably causing confusion with what I named things for ease of the print files.

description.text:
Holds eight SD cards in a compact and easy-to-access array. Minimalist design that can be used in multiple orientations.
The oversimplified look comes from the equality of virtually all dimensions: the slot thickness, distance between cards, side/bottom tab protrusion, and side/bottom wall thickness all have the same measurement. Overall height and width are also equal.
The cards can be placed contacts-up or contacts-down, but I think contacts-down (as shown in every picture so far) looks much better and keeps your fingers off the sensitive parts.
Also uploaded is the first version I made; once I printed it, the cards fit too tightly. I wanted something that would be easy to drop cards into without any stress. You can try the original 'tight' version if you're looking for a more secure fit, maybe if it gets moved around a lot. I imagine either model could simply be scaled overall at the time of printing to achieve a tighter/looser fit.

title: Rigid RigidBot MotherBoard to HeatBed Cable

description.text:
The original RigidBot HeatBed cable uses a flatcable where the Heatbed Power is connected paralellconnection of 4 cables in the flatcable. 4 cables are used for positive HeatBedPower and 4 cables are used for negative HeatBedPower. The termistor is connected to the 2 remaining connections and have no polarity. The original Rigidbot Heatbed cable is not oriented so the cable is bent in a natural way. My belive is that this is the main reason why the cable connectors get warm. Small sparks are created when the connectors are moved due to the stiffness of the cable. The Cable for the HeatBed is 500mm and I used 1.5mm2.
The cable is dimensionion is capable of transfering 20A with voltageloss of 0.4V. ( 0.75mm2 should work but I dubbled that to be sure) The connector-capsulation is higher to prepare room for extrudercables on the Motherboard side and clearance of the Y-bridge in both standard and "heatbed-element-on-top-of-cork-and-glas-abowe" solutions. The cable connection is the same for both RigidBot Regular and RigidBot Big. For users with another type of Motherbord they just use the HeatBed side of the solution.

The cable uses 2 soft silicone cables of 1.5mm2 for Heatbed power. Thermistor cable is a thin flat cable. Solder thin copper wires 25mm long to the crimp connectors. Insert the "long" crimpconnectors in the connectorhouse Solder a 10mm x 20mm exprimental board with offset for the cable Wrap the reminding lead over the edge = create a "thunnel" for the power cables Solder the power cables Solder the termistor cable Trim the sides to fit the encapsulation TEST THE CABLE!!!! Fill the encapsilation with epoxi just to fixate the cables Totaly fill the encapsulation

The calculation of percentage can be performed with
the formula p = W / G, where W stands for the relative
number and G for the whole number. The result p times
100 gives the result in percentage. It is possible to interpret the formula as
as functional equations:
p(W,G) = W / G, W(p,G) = p G, G(W,p) = W / p. The first and and third equation have the form f(x,y) = x / y
and the second one f(x,y) = x y. Two of the three designs
are 3D 'plots' of these functions. They can be used
in the 7th class to provide an additional view
on percentage calculation, or later as an inverse
problem: Find a function with which this shape has
been created! The third design is a 3D 'plot' of the equation for the
kinetic energy: E(m,v) = 1/2 m v^2, with m for mass
and v for velocity. A further application of the objects is to demonstrate
iso-lines by dipping the objects e.g. into colored water. The objects are no "remixes", but have been inspired
by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:24897 .

title: OpenSCAD library - Springs, helicoils, elliptic rings

description.text:
OpenSCAD has some extraordinary xxx_extrude() functionality, which will do a lot astonishing things with just some fingertips. The bad news is: to do quite a lot of things - especially coils - properly, a more sophisticated approach might be required. linear_extrude() will projectively deform your cross sectional shape when coiling helices by use of the twist parameter. You will either have to compensate for that (which is not any more possible in more coiled designs) or take the stony way presented in my lib. Whenever your task is to extrude a shape along a non-circular trajectory like an ellipse, a spring, an elliptical spring, a heart or any other curve in 3D space, the hull() operator is your friend.
The drawback is: It renders slowly and F6 easily may take hours, as I found out producing my sampler for this thing. To give you an idea how the mathematics behind it is knitted, as well as some ready-to-use coiled stuff I packed a little library containing four parametrized modules elliptic_ring(r1 = 10, r2 = 5, r = 2, slices = 100, h = 0, w = 360)
helicoil(Windings = 5, R = 20, r = 1, slices = 50, clockwise = true, square = true)
spring(Windings = 5, R = 20, r=2, h = 20, slices = 50)
elliptic_spring(Windings = 5, R1 = 20, R2 = 0, r=1, h = 20, slices = 50) The code does look neat at the first glace but also somehow strange, since it heavily uses my ShortCuts.scad library, which I have presented in one of my previous projects: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:644830 Sorry for that, but it speeds up my programming so much that I don't want to do without any more. Give it a chance and you'll also fall in love with it. To sum it up, your chart will contain two libs, one referencing the other. Usage examples are shown in the screenshots.

To make the lib available for your code copy Springs.scad and ShortCut.scad into your OpenSCAD libaries folder or current project folder and reference them it by include ShortCut.scad may also used as standalone lib. reference it with include Also note that I put help() functionality into each of my libs. For further instructions concerning ShortCut.scad please refere to http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:644830

title: Quick Release Bosch Colt CNC Spindle Mount

description.text: A quick release mount to attach a Bosch Colt to 20x40mm extrusion rail (Shapeoko and similar). This will allow you to remove the spindle for use as a trim router when you're not milling. Also check out http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:989778, a laser adapter to mount a JTech Photonics laser module or similar into my quick mount.

I printed all files out of PLA on a Makerbot at low quality with 20% infill. If deflection becomes a problem, I will have to print at a higher infill. The pin holes were cleared out with drill bits until the pins fit. The pins have a flat on them so you can print them on their sides to increase shear strength. My counter bores on the mounting holes are a bit deep for the M5x20mm screws I had so I added 3 M5 washers to each. You may need to tweak diameters based on your printers shrink. On mine the collar clamps very snugly, and takes quite a bit of force to lock the cams. Update:
I added a strip of Gorilla tape around the inside diameter of the mount. The compliance of the gorilla tape makes the inside of the mount grippier and tighter overall. After hours of milling work everything is still looking solid. Update (1/8/16):
After a year of use, a failure of a holding tab caused the spindle to get hung up on a cutout, breaking the mount. I strengthened the main components to prevent future issues, and printed with a higher infill. See revision 2 versions of the "mount" and "arm". Please note that the assembly stl has not been updated as of yet. The photo with the black components shows the new updated parts.

title: Hanging Z axis mount for Velleman K8200/3drag with velleman K8204 Trapezoid leadscrew upgrade

description.text:
look here for the second evolution :
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1003914 This is my hanging z-axis Mount for the Velleman K8200/3drag printer
with Velleman K8204 trapezoid leadscrew upgrade. I found the original leadsrcew mount looking quite strange and because of missing upper support for the leadscrew it was kind of wobbly and noisy during print too. Therefore i changed my z axis to have it hanging down from the top of the frame. This gives a bit (about 20mm) mor build height and makes the z movement very smooth. The only parts needed in addition are some screws to fix the follower nut. All other screws for mounting are the ones that came originally with the printer. The Ball bearing is from the stock Z axis mount and the flex coupler for the motor comes with the leadscrew kit. (i chose to keep one i had already in use) To make it easier to tweak the parts, if necessary, i included the 123d Design files as well. Please leave a comment about your experiences and ask if someting is unclear.

IMPORTANT!
You will need to reverse the Z axis direction in your firmware after
mounting the motor top down! You will need each part once.
Print with 0.2mm to 0.25mm layer height and 30% infill. After mounting the leadscrew into the bearing clamp it tight from top and bottom between the flex coupler and the printed "counter" nut".
Make sure the bearing sits fix in the holder. If if moves, use glue to fix it. Align the motor and follower nut properly, so the leadscrew goes though the bearing without tension to one side. The motor mount sits quite stiff without additional fixing, but it can be fixed with screws too, if necessary.

description.text: A sweetener holder and swizzle stick tray for your desk. Based on Sweetener Holder by Makerblock.

Last week my old hand shower broke. I decided to print a new one myself. This is a work in progress, I still need to print it, so try at your own risk :-). EDIT: 24 jan 2015: replaced original by V2, lying flat on the bed, inside tringle imptoved for better quality still without support inside. Some support recommended for the bottom of the screwable part only EDIT2: 24 jan 2015: FInished printing with 100% infill. Well, It leaks like hell. I wonder if it would soften seawater though, cause leaks do have to go between lots of layers to get out :-). Now trying to make one with much more side layers (6) and a 110% global extrusion workflow, 20% infill. Keep you posted! EDIT3: Urrah! The solution was: 110% extrusion flow; 10% infill and 6 layers top bottom sides. I got only one microleak on the front head of the shower, and the holes should be drawn a bit bigger to compensate the 110% extrusion, but besides that, We've got a simple printed working shower handle! Tip of the day: to adjust the extrusion flow, you may also lie on the filament section: f.e; 1.75 / 110 * 100 = 1.59
